04468nam a22005775i 9780822389460DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223894607 a10.1515/97808223894602doi  a(DE-B1597)552807  a(OCoLC)1224278108  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1532b.G86 2009 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a361.6/509822221 aGuy, Donna J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen Build the Welfare State :bPerforming Charity and Creating Rights in Argentina, 1880-1955 /cDonna J. Guy. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b18 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Female Philanthropy and Feminism before the Welfare State -- tBenevolence and Female Volunteerism -- tPerforming Child Welfare -- t4. Juvenile Delinquency, Patriarchy, and Female Philanthropy -- t5. The Depression and the Rise of the Welfare State -- t6. At the Crossroads of Change -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this pathbreaking history, Donna J. Guy shows how feminists, social workers, and female philanthropists contributed to the emergence of the Argentine welfare state through their advocacy of child welfare and family-law reform. From the creation of the government-subsidized Society of Beneficence in 1823, women were at the forefront of the child-focused philanthropic and municipal groups that proliferated first to address the impact of urbanization, European immigration, and high infant mortality rates, and later to meet the needs of wayward, abandoned, and delinquent children. Women staffed child-centered organizations that received subsidies from all levels of government. Their interest in children also led them into the battle for female suffrage and the campaign to promote the legal adoption of children. When Juan Perón expanded the welfare system during his presidency (1946-1955), he reorganized private charitable organizations that had, until then, often been led by elite and immigrant women.Drawing on extensive research in Argentine archives, Guy reveals significant continuities in Argentine history, including the rise of a liberal state that subsidized all kinds of women's and religious groups. State and private welfare efforts became more organized in the 1930s and reached a pinnacle under Juan Perón, when men took over the welfare state and philanthropic and feminist women's influence on child-welfare activities and policy declined. Comparing the rise of Argentina's welfare state with the development of others around the world, Guy considers both why women's child-welfare initiatives have not received more attention in historical accounts and whether the welfare state emerges from the top down or from the bottom up.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aFeministszArgentina. 0aWelfare statezArgentina. 0aWomen in charitable workzArgentina. 0aWomen philanthropistszArgentina. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzArgentina. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822389460zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822389460423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822389460.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles